1
00:00:00,470 --> 00:00:02,072
Fear.

2
00:00:03,794 --> 00:00:04,134
Fear.

3
00:00:12,205 --> 00:00:23,778
What the meditation is trying to do is trying to get you in contact with fear before you call it fear.

4
00:00:26,121 --> 00:00:28,806
What's fear before you recognize it as fear?

5
00:00:29,365 --> 00:00:29,986
What is it?

6
00:00:34,978 --> 00:00:35,979
It's a bit nauseating.

7
00:00:37,701 --> 00:00:39,744
It's sort of an uncomfortable feeling in the body.

8
00:00:42,667 --> 00:00:47,994
As soon as the mind recognises it as fear, it categorises it, blocks it.

9
00:00:49,597 --> 00:00:51,920
And as soon as it's done that, it'll react.

10
00:00:53,021 --> 00:00:55,503
It'll start being afraid of fear.

11
00:00:55,524 --> 00:00:56,826
And that's how we suppress stuff.

12
00:00:56,845 --> 00:00:58,328
We just push it away with fear.

13
00:00:58,548 --> 00:01:00,210
It's sort of just, don't want to see it.

14
00:01:02,536 --> 00:01:06,819
So you can't get right down there, you've got to go through those little two barriers.

15
00:01:07,941 --> 00:01:17,951
So when fear arises, this is in your meditation now, when fear arises, you first of all have to hold steady and just feel that panic.

16
00:01:18,012 --> 00:01:20,713
See, the panic's the fear of the fear, which is making you run.

17
00:01:21,936 --> 00:01:24,739
You just hang on in there, you wait for it to die down.

18
00:01:24,959 --> 00:01:28,121
And then what you're building up is bravery, isn't it?

19
00:01:28,878 --> 00:01:32,545
Bravery is being able to stand in the midst of fear, not move.

20
00:01:33,167 --> 00:01:34,468
Yeah?

21
00:01:34,489 --> 00:01:36,694
So you stand there, you see.

22
00:01:36,713 --> 00:01:40,781
And then as your reaction goes away, you're still shaking from the fear, you see.

23
00:01:41,283 --> 00:01:44,709
So then you get interested in it, not as an emotion.

24
00:01:45,111 --> 00:01:48,697
Because that immediately brings up all sorts of concepts and ideas.

25
00:01:50,478 --> 00:01:55,807
You can even get into a sort of wild goose chase of trying to find out why you're afraid.

26
00:01:56,507 --> 00:01:58,390
Get into a personal therapy.

27
00:02:00,313 --> 00:02:06,141
When you get into a personal therapy, just remind yourself that it's the deluded trying to find out how they're deluded.

28
00:02:07,689 --> 00:02:14,039
And the definition of delusion is, you don't know where the delusion is, so you wouldn't be deluded.

29
00:02:16,062 --> 00:02:25,298
So, when fear comes up and you try and chase some sort of historical moment when all this fear was gathered, then actually all you're doing is not facing the fear.

30
00:02:25,818 --> 00:02:27,842
You're trying to get behind it or before it.

31
00:02:28,483 --> 00:02:31,167
And even if you did remember the occasion, would it help?

32
00:02:32,158 --> 00:02:35,609
So okay, it was when your mother hit you with a banana across the ear when you were three years old.

33
00:02:36,151 --> 00:02:37,234
So what?

34
00:02:37,253 --> 00:02:38,396
You're still stuck with the fear.

35
00:02:39,019 --> 00:02:40,683
You're still stuck with the aftermath.

36
00:02:41,609 --> 00:02:44,573
So one has to get into the feel of it.

37
00:02:44,793 --> 00:02:52,122
So then you point your attention to the quality of its feeling, its sensations, the sensations it's calling.

38
00:02:53,082 --> 00:02:55,406
And as you go into it, you taste it.

39
00:02:56,807 --> 00:02:58,310
You get a feel for fear.

40
00:02:59,790 --> 00:03:01,813
And you just sit in the midst of that.

41
00:03:01,834 --> 00:03:04,377
And when you sit in the midst of fear,

42
00:03:04,356 --> 00:03:05,418
What's happening?

43
00:03:06,419 --> 00:03:10,062
It's just a mental, physical turbulence, isn't it?

44
00:03:10,824 --> 00:03:15,969
It's like a bit of bad weather running through the organism, isn't it?

45
00:03:16,770 --> 00:03:21,135
You're just sat there just with this nausea or something.

46
00:03:21,156 --> 00:03:23,739
It's pitting your stomach or you might have it in your chest.

47
00:03:24,438 --> 00:03:26,701
You're just sitting there, that's it.

48
00:03:29,854 --> 00:03:32,057
You babysit.

49
00:03:32,078 --> 00:03:32,758
Just sit with it.

50
00:03:33,599 --> 00:03:36,503
And as you're sitting with it, you might notice that it's a process.

51
00:03:37,406 --> 00:03:40,770
You might notice that there's no such thing as, this is fear.

52
00:03:40,991 --> 00:03:44,816
It's just a set of arising and passing away of sensations.

53
00:03:44,915 --> 00:03:46,337
They're just little sensations.

54
00:03:47,680 --> 00:03:53,127
And you might get that feeling that actually, to be in the midst of that isn't suffering.

55
00:03:54,931 --> 00:03:57,014
It's only suffering when you start reacting to it.

56
00:03:57,413 --> 00:03:59,456
It's only suffering when the fear of fear arises.

57
00:04:00,937 --> 00:04:03,966
And then when you get comfortable with the fear, it's okay, you want more of it.

58
00:04:05,631 --> 00:04:05,931
See?

59
00:04:05,951 --> 00:04:08,799
You just sat there with it and said, well, come on, let's show your face.

60
00:04:09,260 --> 00:04:10,683
It's like a snake, show your face.

61
00:04:12,068 --> 00:04:14,855
So we just let it come up, let it come up.

62
00:04:14,876 --> 00:04:17,141
Now, when you let things come up like that,

63
00:04:18,791 --> 00:04:37,910
Because you're not identifying with it, I am afraid, because you're not pushing it away, feeding the system with fear, with more fear, because you're not turning away in aversion, because you're not trying to seek its origin, because you're not trying to do anything with it, you're therefore not empowering it at all.

64
00:04:39,632 --> 00:04:43,935
In which case, like any energy form, it has entropy.

65
00:04:44,576 --> 00:04:45,357
It will die away.

66
00:04:45,396 --> 00:04:47,178
It dies away.

67
00:04:48,154 --> 00:04:53,833
And then you recognize that actually all you have to do with fear is sit with it.

68
00:04:54,595 --> 00:04:54,956
Hug it.

69
00:04:56,339 --> 00:04:59,750
I don't want to sound too New Agey there, but just sit with it.

70
00:05:00,911 --> 00:05:02,995
And then it passes.

71
00:05:03,154 --> 00:05:03,935
It passes.

72
00:05:03,956 --> 00:05:05,358
And that's where your confidence comes.

73
00:05:06,901 --> 00:05:09,603
And then you translate that to all your negative states.

74
00:05:09,805 --> 00:05:12,449
Depression, stress, whatever it is.

75
00:05:13,250 --> 00:05:15,091
And you realize you don't have to do anything at all.

76
00:05:16,113 --> 00:05:20,560
You just have to sit in the midst of the flames.

77
00:05:20,579 --> 00:05:21,901
That's all.

78
00:05:21,922 --> 00:05:23,764
And it arises and passes away.

79
00:05:25,567 --> 00:05:26,028
And that's it.

80
00:05:27,230 --> 00:05:27,891
End of fear.

81
00:05:28,971 --> 00:05:30,834
Guaranteed 40 years.

82
00:05:34,307 --> 00:05:37,072
if you're lucky, because there's a lot down there.

83
00:05:37,875 --> 00:05:39,757
It's not as though you're going to get rid of it.

84
00:05:40,178 --> 00:05:46,670
So any ideas of getting rid of fear is also a sort of subtle aversion.

85
00:05:48,093 --> 00:05:49,997
You mustn't have any opinion about it.

86
00:05:50,416 --> 00:05:56,247
What you're really trying to discover is just how to be with it in a non-reactive way.

87
00:05:57,494 --> 00:06:07,976
In so doing, you find, as it were, a place within yourself which is aloof.

88
00:06:08,879 --> 00:06:09,579
It's up above.

89
00:06:09,620 --> 00:06:15,552
Even though you're in it, you're not of it.

90
00:06:17,355 --> 00:06:19,137
So that's what the Buddha's teaching.

91
00:06:19,257 --> 00:06:20,779
That's the position we have to take.

92
00:06:22,041 --> 00:06:24,985
In the body and mind, in the heart, but not of it.

93
00:06:25,706 --> 00:06:31,593
So that sense of being aloof, of being an observer, an experiencer, a witness.

94
00:06:34,297 --> 00:06:38,201
You can get there by just an act of will, by saying, you know, this is an object.

95
00:06:38,262 --> 00:06:39,824
You can point to it and say fear.

96
00:06:39,863 --> 00:06:42,586
As soon as you point to something, it's an object.

97
00:06:42,922 --> 00:06:44,564
So it can't be you, it can't be me.

98
00:06:46,565 --> 00:06:49,949
You're already creating a distance just by recognizing it's there.

99
00:06:54,035 --> 00:06:56,278
That's not the end point to be an observer.

100
00:06:56,737 --> 00:06:58,240
The end point is pure observing.

101
00:06:58,279 --> 00:07:01,644
Even that sense of some body observing disappears.

102
00:07:02,305 --> 00:07:03,745
But that just arises naturally.

103
00:07:03,766 --> 00:07:04,788
You don't have to work at that.

104
00:07:08,312 --> 00:07:09,312
So that's fear.

105
00:07:10,053 --> 00:07:11,055
I wouldn't worry about it.

106
00:07:18,223 --> 00:07:24,050
There's nothing around that in terms of how you meditate with it, how you actually sit with it.

107
00:07:29,295 --> 00:07:34,300
The good thing about strong emotions is that you've, generally speaking, got no problems with concentration.

108
00:07:40,548 --> 00:07:40,827
Can I ask?

109
00:07:40,848 --> 00:07:40,949
Yeah.

110
00:07:40,968 --> 00:07:46,053
Would you say that then if you feel fear in a situation which isn't,

111
00:07:46,608 --> 00:07:54,322
sitting on the cushion in the situation, that that would be the best approach to adopt?

112
00:07:54,341 --> 00:07:55,863
I'm coming to that in a minute.

113
00:07:56,084 --> 00:07:57,427
Fear in action, as it were.

114
00:07:57,466 --> 00:07:58,970
What about this?

115
00:07:59,531 --> 00:08:02,214
Are you all pretty clear about fear when you're sitting?

116
00:08:04,579 --> 00:08:06,523
You're getting to know it intimately.

117
00:08:10,199 --> 00:08:12,541
So you have to be aware of your reactions to it too.

118
00:08:13,081 --> 00:08:14,103
That's all.

119
00:08:14,122 --> 00:08:15,764
Come off all head stuff.

120
00:08:15,805 --> 00:08:18,968
As soon as you start thinking, imaging something, cut.

121
00:08:19,468 --> 00:08:20,389
Come down to the body.

122
00:08:22,052 --> 00:08:25,076
Because that's how an emotion develops itself, through thought.

123
00:08:30,341 --> 00:08:35,126
It's through the technique of imaginative thinking that emotions develop themselves.

124
00:08:37,908 --> 00:08:51,201
You all know that from when somebody says some little thing that upsets you in the morning and then quite unwittingly you keep thinking about it and thinking about it and thinking about it.

125
00:08:52,041 --> 00:09:02,071
By the evening you're chucking them out of the window and doing all sorts of nasty things and all day you've made them insult you.

126
00:09:02,551 --> 00:09:04,253
And they only did it once.

127
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:13,927
And it's just because that little irritation has grown and grown through the force of our imagination.

128
00:09:14,649 --> 00:09:22,197
So imagination, any thought around fear, you just recognize it as fear and then you come back into the body.

129
00:09:22,476 --> 00:09:23,618
So doing you stop it.

130
00:09:24,178 --> 00:09:35,049
So now that feeling of fear has only one place to come out, which is through the body as a feeling.

131
00:09:36,615 --> 00:09:46,812
So if you think of the mind as a sort of energy system like the weather, or this is just a bit of a storm coming up, see, let it come and let it pass away.

132
00:09:52,495 --> 00:09:53,155
Yeah, is that?

133
00:09:53,796 --> 00:09:54,216
Got the idea?

134
00:09:55,158 --> 00:09:55,918
Yeah.

135
00:09:55,938 --> 00:10:00,504
So now, in all the daily life, of course, it's a different position.

136
00:10:01,245 --> 00:10:10,955
When you're meditating, you're at the interface, you might say, between consciousness and thoughts, consciousness and emotions, consciousness and sensations in the body.

137
00:10:11,635 --> 00:10:15,059
When you're meditating like that, ask yourself, where's the personality?

138
00:10:18,077 --> 00:10:23,977
It's only when you get up and speak and do that suddenly a personality appears, a personal writing.

139
00:10:24,659 --> 00:10:26,586
When you're looking inside yourself, what do you see?

140
00:10:27,830 --> 00:10:28,251
A thought?

141
00:10:28,793 --> 00:10:29,556
An emotion?

142
00:10:31,442 --> 00:10:36,567
So this becoming of a personality is a different position.

143
00:10:36,607 --> 00:10:42,734
You're in now the flow of your actions and your speech.

144
00:10:43,674 --> 00:10:56,488
So now, when fear comes up, or anxiety comes up in action, then, as it were, we've still got to try to maintain just that sense of knowing it's there.

145
00:10:56,467 --> 00:10:58,471
Knowing it's there, you see?

146
00:10:58,831 --> 00:11:01,855
And because of that knowing it's there, you've lifted yourself out of it.

147
00:11:02,697 --> 00:11:05,160
Even though this is saying, run, run, run, run, you see?

148
00:11:05,461 --> 00:11:06,201
You keep walking.

149
00:11:09,086 --> 00:11:13,371
Because you've not fallen into the delusion of the fear.

150
00:11:13,852 --> 00:11:19,120
So even though the fear is tearing at you and they're saying, run, run, run, run, you keep walking, you keep walking.

151
00:11:19,140 --> 00:11:19,961
Because you're above it.

152
00:11:23,705 --> 00:11:27,631
And if you feel it's the same thing, when the panic comes, you say, just stop, hang on in there.

153
00:11:29,755 --> 00:11:30,677
You can't handle it, run.

154
00:11:32,782 --> 00:11:35,046
It's alright.

155
00:11:35,066 --> 00:11:38,392
And then when it passes, just reflect on that.

156
00:11:38,412 --> 00:11:39,333
Hmm, that's interesting.

157
00:11:41,542 --> 00:11:47,250
And so in other words, you've got to take your meditation, this insight, into daily life.

158
00:11:48,152 --> 00:11:56,884
And don't worry if you so-called don't succeed, because all that's shown is the strength of our conditioning.

159
00:11:57,105 --> 00:11:58,486
So that takes a little humility.

160
00:11:59,688 --> 00:12:01,532
This is the way it is at the moment.

161
00:12:01,552 --> 00:12:03,094
But you work gently against it.

162
00:12:09,436 --> 00:12:14,520
Even if you have a very strong sort of fear, like obsessional stuff.

163
00:12:17,384 --> 00:12:21,129
One person who worked with me had problems with contamination.

164
00:12:22,690 --> 00:12:26,014
Couldn't go near certain areas that had been contaminated with certain substances.

165
00:12:27,875 --> 00:12:38,447
And I was just trying really to, through the meditation, to get her to have enough confidence that she could stay within that fear.

166
00:12:39,541 --> 00:12:46,630
and then to try to get the person to walk into that contaminated area.

167
00:12:50,076 --> 00:12:50,177
Yeah?

168
00:12:50,197 --> 00:12:56,365
So, in this case it didn't work that way.

169
00:12:56,807 --> 00:13:09,345
If you take that as an example, so we all have fear, we all have anxieties and this and that, so it's a case of knowing that it can't kill you, it's only an emotion that comes out,

170
00:13:10,033 --> 00:13:16,605
And then just building up through your own self, through your own reflection to move towards that area which is dangerous.

171
00:13:17,365 --> 00:13:17,966
Hang on in there.

172
00:13:18,849 --> 00:13:20,510
Stay there, just keep moving towards it.

173
00:13:25,499 --> 00:13:27,241
Now ultimately, what's the ultimate point?

174
00:13:27,482 --> 00:13:30,206
The ultimate point is the loss of fear of fear.

175
00:13:32,090 --> 00:13:36,177
And when you've lost your fear of fear, what's going to frighten you?

176
00:13:40,712 --> 00:13:43,196
It's at that point that fear drops away.

177
00:13:43,255 --> 00:13:51,527
And that's why, through your meditation, you should see that there's a possibility of the end of fear, the complete ending of fear.

178
00:13:58,676 --> 00:13:58,897
Yeah?

179
00:14:02,500 --> 00:14:03,682
Anything around that?

180
00:14:13,956 --> 00:14:42,342
Well, you should worry about fear.

181
00:14:42,998 --> 00:14:45,500
But when is there a situation when you should worry about fear?

182
00:14:46,922 --> 00:14:47,602
Is that the question?

183
00:14:49,144 --> 00:14:54,291
Yeah, I was kind of asking, I was thinking about questions this morning.

184
00:14:54,311 --> 00:14:58,254
I was thinking about fear more after the weekend.

185
00:14:59,976 --> 00:15:02,198
We've been talking about it a bit.

186
00:15:04,422 --> 00:15:10,187
But when you project fear onto a situation which isn't really fearful, it feels so real.

187
00:15:10,489 --> 00:15:12,650
So how really to distinguish between

188
00:15:12,985 --> 00:15:22,296
real fear and be sensible about it, and what you've projected from your own mind, it's quite hard.

189
00:15:22,395 --> 00:15:23,857
Yes, of course that's difficult.

190
00:15:24,337 --> 00:15:35,971
I mean, you can take a sort of absolutist stance and say that all fear is false projection, but obviously there is a level where it becomes inappropriate, shall we say.

191
00:15:35,951 --> 00:15:39,937
It's not fixed to the actual situation.

192
00:15:40,379 --> 00:15:54,321
As the case that I've just pointed out, this particular person, if some substance or other, if she thought that some substance or other was in this room, she couldn't go into it.

193
00:15:54,341 --> 00:15:55,724
And it was irrational.

194
00:15:56,183 --> 00:15:57,166
She was irrational.

195
00:15:57,405 --> 00:15:58,727
It wasn't as though she was crazy.

196
00:15:59,690 --> 00:16:01,032
But she couldn't go into that room.

197
00:16:02,767 --> 00:16:09,418
So often you can perceive that your fear is irrational.

198
00:16:10,023 --> 00:16:14,649
For instance, if you have, on holiday, you have a fear of jumping off the high board at the swimming pool.

199
00:16:15,932 --> 00:16:18,696
Fear is irrational, isn't it?

200
00:16:18,716 --> 00:16:20,859
So, if you have that fear, you go up there and do it.

201
00:16:20,899 --> 00:16:25,926
You keep doing it until the fear, until you've actually, until you've no fear of it.

202
00:16:25,946 --> 00:16:33,918
But in so doing it with meditation, you're actually learning how to be with fear and not to let it hijack you.

203
00:16:35,921 --> 00:16:39,725
Now, there comes that shady area where you don't know whether

204
00:16:39,706 --> 00:16:43,410
Whether it's fear or not, whether it's appropriate fear or not.

205
00:16:43,932 --> 00:16:46,034
In which case, what can you do?

206
00:16:46,054 --> 00:16:47,277
You have to test it.

207
00:16:50,240 --> 00:16:59,835
You can only investigate a situation and find out whether in fact your fear was correct or not.

208
00:16:59,975 --> 00:17:00,355
How else?

209
00:17:01,136 --> 00:17:02,078
You don't know, you see.

210
00:17:02,318 --> 00:17:03,561
That's the problem with delusion.

211
00:17:03,600 --> 00:17:04,301
You just don't know.

212
00:17:04,321 --> 00:17:05,763
You have to keep testing things.

213
00:17:28,188 --> 00:17:29,871
Any questions around that?

214
00:17:29,971 --> 00:17:48,680
In its sort of biological origin, I mean, I think it's like a... You'd think that it would be programmed to have fear of something, a self-protection, and that you'd actually be quite heightened perception.

215
00:17:49,602 --> 00:17:52,946
So it's sort of that you'd have the fear in order to be able to

216
00:17:55,238 --> 00:18:16,268
We're so used to running away from emotions, but you can imagine that the fear was actually a heightened sense in order to deal with something, so that you're actually in a state where you can think all your senses are alert, which is sort of what you should be anyway, but we're so used to

217
00:18:16,483 --> 00:18:28,316
like negative emotions, like, you've got to run away from the emotion, rather than it has a function or it has, whether its function is present or past, that you're just to use it or stay with it or go through it.

218
00:18:28,536 --> 00:18:31,618
Yeah, absolutely.

219
00:18:31,859 --> 00:18:41,209
I mean, there should be, shall we say, that background fear, for want of a better word, whenever we're crossing a busy road, isn't it?

220
00:18:42,421 --> 00:18:46,575
It's just that the fear then becomes a sort of guardian.

221
00:18:47,045 --> 00:18:54,374
where you never actually feel the fear, but the fear is running as it were in the background because you know if you make a mistake you're going to get run over.

222
00:18:55,875 --> 00:18:59,980
This is much the same as shame, dread, guilt.

223
00:19:01,962 --> 00:19:10,573
When we do something which is unskillful, unwholesome, then these emotions arise, these states of mind arise.

224
00:19:12,694 --> 00:19:16,680
But what the Buddha calls them, guardians of society.

225
00:19:17,773 --> 00:19:33,073
not in the sense that they are wholesome because we've done something wrong, but when we've done something wrong and we've felt the inner reaction of shame, dread and guilt, then as it were, it's just like that background program.

226
00:19:33,093 --> 00:19:46,971
So the Buddha says, you can get sensitive enough so that as soon as an unskillful, unwholesome idea arises in the mind, it recoils, you see, it recoils like a feather from the flame.

227
00:19:46,951 --> 00:19:52,371
And that's that inner conditioning about, well if I do this, this is what's going to happen.

228
00:19:56,738 --> 00:20:10,693
And I dare say that there are sort of inbuilt fear mechanisms just in the mind itself, which is self-protective.

229
00:20:10,713 --> 00:20:15,940
But that's not the same as what we're talking about, in a sense, because that just arises and passes away when it's pure.

230
00:20:16,079 --> 00:20:17,701
Oops, don't go there.

231
00:20:17,721 --> 00:20:18,462
That's it, it's gone.

232
00:20:18,903 --> 00:20:22,627
It's like the heart telling you, you know, there's danger there.

233
00:20:23,569 --> 00:20:31,060
See, that's totally different from the normal fears and anxieties that we feel ordinarily.

234
00:20:34,226 --> 00:20:34,527
Isn't it?

235
00:20:37,631 --> 00:20:37,811
No?

236
00:20:38,492 --> 00:20:38,732
Yes?

237
00:20:41,897 --> 00:20:47,906
I just think that that would have a sort of a different function, a different feel even to the fear.

238
00:20:50,366 --> 00:20:56,012
Don't we rush it up by the use of the word fear when it's actually lower than anxiety?

239
00:20:57,054 --> 00:21:08,684
Oh, well, that's what I meant about as soon as you label it, you categorize it and then all your history comes in and before you know it, you're stuck with an ogre, where in fact it was just a little tickling in the stomach.

240
00:21:10,406 --> 00:21:12,489
A little tickle in the solar plexus.

241
00:21:12,509 --> 00:21:13,108
Yeah, definitely.

242
00:21:14,309 --> 00:21:17,032
That's the problem with history.

243
00:21:23,644 --> 00:21:41,400
I mean, my own personal opinion is that the fully liberated person wouldn't feel fear at all, apart from that sort of fear of just knowing something is dangerous, as a background understanding, you might say.

244
00:21:43,996 --> 00:21:53,911
just on the grounds that there's no association at all anymore, there's no identity or wrong understanding of what this body, mind and heart is.

245
00:21:57,435 --> 00:22:05,828
Once it's not you, it's not a big problem, is it?

246
00:22:05,848 --> 00:22:12,618
You see, you can intellectualize, you can rationalize and say, well, I know my body's not me, it's going to die, etc., etc.

247
00:22:14,759 --> 00:22:22,134
But then when the doctor tells you you've got six weeks to go, you freak out.

248
00:22:22,154 --> 00:22:34,522
So there's a difference between a sort of intellectual grasp of something, an understanding of something, and actually moving to that level of consciousness which no longer identifies with the body.

249
00:22:47,969 --> 00:22:49,431
But I dare say it's root stuff.

250
00:22:49,510 --> 00:22:58,441
I mean, the place where these emotions are kept, the amygdala or something, I think that's what they call it, comes from reptilian life, doesn't it?

251
00:22:59,521 --> 00:23:03,666
I mean, it's part of that whole evolution of basic life, yeah.

252
00:23:05,107 --> 00:23:13,857
The reason that our emotions, it seems, are civilized is because they're all channeled through the front part of the brain, which is new to human beings, it seems.

253
00:23:17,247 --> 00:23:35,732
But when they escape, that's when you get the road rage, computer rage, things like that.

254
00:23:35,752 --> 00:23:38,817
Was there anything else around that?

255
00:23:44,163 --> 00:23:46,787
Was there another question?

256
00:23:46,807 --> 00:24:13,443
I had the experience last week of leaving the barn for a week and travelling around and staying in different houses and I found it very difficult to keep my meditation practice going and the mindfulness in a sense and I'm wondering if you had any kind of pointers towards kind of maintaining

257
00:24:17,238 --> 00:24:21,304
Yeah, maintaining practice on the road.

258
00:24:21,364 --> 00:24:25,471
Yeah, well, that's the big difficulty, isn't it?

259
00:24:25,490 --> 00:24:32,801
First of all, you just have to recognize that a place like this, a meditation, there are special conditions.

260
00:24:35,086 --> 00:24:37,710
People try not to disturb you for a start.

261
00:24:39,309 --> 00:24:51,404
Generally speaking, people try to respect your silence and respect what you're doing, which isn't so in the outside world, so to speak.

262
00:24:51,425 --> 00:25:06,684
So, you'll never get the same quality in ordinary daily life from what you do in the center until there's been a real, I would say, a real purge of the heart.

263
00:25:06,664 --> 00:25:16,377
So I think it's unrealistic to think that you're just going to walk out of a meditation center or the barn like this and sort of take it with you.

264
00:25:18,461 --> 00:25:26,090
So it's a case of recognizing that you have to put in some sort of coping mechanisms.

265
00:25:27,269 --> 00:25:31,420
So it's very much a case of keeping up the practice morning and evening.

266
00:25:32,061 --> 00:25:39,320
See, the morning is a time when you remind yourself what level of consciousness you want to be at during the day.

267
00:25:40,297 --> 00:25:43,181
And the evening, I don't mean just figure a bed, just fall asleep.

268
00:25:44,083 --> 00:25:54,298
In the evening, say, after work or before you eat, to sit and just let whatever you've accumulated during the day just arise and pass away.

269
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:58,263
Then, of course, you have a very pleasant meal and a more pleasant evening.

270
00:26:01,009 --> 00:26:04,874
The other thing is just simple things like if you find yourself rushing, stop.

271
00:26:04,894 --> 00:26:05,275
Stop.

272
00:26:12,190 --> 00:26:14,093
One thing at a time.

273
00:26:15,894 --> 00:26:16,355
Breathe.

274
00:26:21,262 --> 00:26:25,429
When you're talking to somebody, remind yourself to listen.

275
00:26:27,471 --> 00:26:32,880
If you've got the answer ready before they finish, you're not listening.

276
00:26:32,900 --> 00:26:34,762
You can't listen and answer at the same time.

277
00:26:34,782 --> 00:26:35,865
The brain can't do that.

278
00:26:36,726 --> 00:26:40,932
So you're presuming what they're going to say and you've already given them an answer.

279
00:26:42,463 --> 00:26:47,690
So it's sort of just relaxing into what's happening.

280
00:26:47,710 --> 00:26:50,873
And of course what you find is that when you do that, the other person does it.

281
00:26:51,614 --> 00:26:53,155
Yesterday it was rather funny really.

282
00:26:54,416 --> 00:27:05,670
I'd gone to a cafe with somebody to have a little coffee and then we were walking back because we were trying to open another bank account for this trust we had.

283
00:27:06,375 --> 00:27:18,864
As we were walking there, the pace sort of lifted and halfway through, Anne, and some of you know Anne Ashton, she said to me, God, you're walking fast.

284
00:27:18,943 --> 00:27:22,291
And I said, I thought you were walking fast.

285
00:27:22,271 --> 00:27:25,979
And we were just firing off each other without knowing it.

286
00:27:26,740 --> 00:27:29,685
So, by the end of it, I was running to this damn bank.

287
00:27:32,951 --> 00:27:36,759
So, it's a case of just recognizing that, you know, perhaps the coffee was too strong.

288
00:27:37,279 --> 00:27:37,980
Maybe that's what did it.

289
00:27:42,829 --> 00:27:43,892
And to...

290
00:27:45,188 --> 00:27:59,502
If we're sharp enough, if we can maintain that sort of sharp of mindfulness and recognize that mindfulness or awareness, it doesn't have to be trapped into one single object.

291
00:27:59,522 --> 00:28:00,503
It can be quite wide.

292
00:28:00,963 --> 00:28:11,414
Even now, you see, as you're sort of listening to me, and that's where, as you would say, the point of your attention is, you can still be slightly aware of the bird chirping out there.

293
00:28:14,163 --> 00:28:15,884
and just the colours in the room.

294
00:28:16,405 --> 00:28:20,529
It's like that sort of wide awareness, a wide sort of awareness.

295
00:28:20,810 --> 00:28:22,531
And to get that, you have to be very relaxed.

296
00:28:23,153 --> 00:28:34,125
As soon as you get tight, the whole thing sort of... And so it's that sort of effort just to keep relaxing, you know, feel your shoulders and... You know, just let the breath go for a little while.

297
00:28:35,366 --> 00:28:38,711
Then you just have to keep doing it and keep doing it and keep doing it.

298
00:28:40,292 --> 00:28:42,414
And just very slowly you...

299
00:28:43,423 --> 00:28:45,145
Try to take life easy.

300
00:28:45,586 --> 00:28:49,570
And then little reflections like, does it help to rush?

301
00:28:50,172 --> 00:28:51,933
Does it help to get irritated?

302
00:28:52,954 --> 00:28:53,915
What does it do?

303
00:28:54,457 --> 00:28:55,597
What's the point of it?

304
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:01,464
It doesn't mean that we don't get irritated and we don't rush.

305
00:29:01,484 --> 00:29:11,696
It's just that we're trying to slowly work against these old habits which are deeply ingrained and are reinforced by society.

306
00:29:11,957 --> 00:29:12,958
This is the problem.

307
00:29:13,511 --> 00:29:27,015
I mean, if you were to stay here for, I don't know, a year or so, then it would begin to undermine a certain conditioning.

308
00:29:40,646 --> 00:29:44,734
But the effort has to be made because the one feeds into the other.

309
00:29:44,775 --> 00:29:53,070
If you meditate, say, for a week or something and then go out and have sex, drugs and rock and roll, then you've had it, you see.

310
00:29:53,111 --> 00:30:01,727
You come back and you've still got these headaches and backaches and it's as though you've got to take it into daily life, you see.

311
00:30:03,614 --> 00:30:08,310
And don't expect great change, very slow.

312
00:30:09,555 --> 00:30:12,003
It comes over a long period of time.

313
00:30:26,699 --> 00:30:27,460
There's no...

314
00:30:27,480 --> 00:30:30,845
I remember once when I came back from...

315
00:30:30,865 --> 00:30:40,257
I'd been out in the eaves meditating and a very old friend of mine came up who's a long-time meditator and his first question was, is there a quicker way?

316
00:30:42,599 --> 00:30:45,203
That was the only thing he was actually concerned with.

317
00:30:45,223 --> 00:30:46,526
Is there a quicker way than this?

318
00:30:49,569 --> 00:30:53,414
I'm afraid that... Well, I mean, if you find one, come and tell me about it and say...

319
00:31:10,777 --> 00:31:14,560
Stopping is a very strong technique.

320
00:31:15,662 --> 00:31:21,128
If you leave a room, for instance, and you've picked up a bit of irritation there.

321
00:31:22,250 --> 00:31:28,636
If you just open the door, close the door, just mindfully, and then just stand for a moment and just recognize what's happening.

322
00:31:29,478 --> 00:31:33,982
And then just wait for it to sort of die out a little.

323
00:31:33,962 --> 00:31:36,486
then you find it doesn't snowball, you see.

324
00:31:36,506 --> 00:31:38,887
You don't take it with you into the next room and off it goes.

325
00:31:39,328 --> 00:31:41,310
So you ratchet things up all the time.

326
00:31:52,742 --> 00:31:53,403
Any other questions?

327
00:31:58,950 --> 00:32:00,612
Just a question about...

328
00:32:01,942 --> 00:32:15,630
Right effort, that sort of balance between too much effort and not enough, the technique to sort of find the best way to sort of...

329
00:32:16,336 --> 00:32:19,359
Concentrate too much, but not put too much pressure on it.

330
00:32:19,760 --> 00:32:24,666
But, you know, hanging in an easy... Yeah.

331
00:32:25,508 --> 00:32:27,190
Just in particular meditation.

332
00:32:27,210 --> 00:32:28,132
In particular meditation.

333
00:32:28,152 --> 00:32:28,251
Yeah.

334
00:32:28,592 --> 00:32:29,512
Ah.

335
00:32:29,532 --> 00:32:34,901
Well, I've always thought that's pretty easy, actually, to get over that one.

336
00:32:35,441 --> 00:32:38,484
Because we are Westerners, we have to achieve.

337
00:32:39,487 --> 00:32:39,646
Okay?

338
00:32:40,347 --> 00:32:42,631
So, make your achievement just being aware.

339
00:32:42,931 --> 00:32:45,094
That is the achievement, to be aware.

340
00:32:46,086 --> 00:32:46,468
That's it.

341
00:32:46,907 --> 00:32:49,051
You don't have to worry about insights.

342
00:32:49,432 --> 00:32:50,815
Just be aware of what's happening.

343
00:32:50,994 --> 00:32:56,243
Put the whole of your effort in just knowing what's actually happening now.

344
00:32:56,304 --> 00:33:03,234
As soon as you put any expectation to it, as soon as you put an idea to it,

345
00:33:04,311 --> 00:33:17,334
then of course you are bringing some sort of extra to that present moment-to-moment awareness.

346
00:33:17,354 --> 00:33:21,221
So you're not looking for anything, you're just looking at what's coming up.

347
00:33:23,324 --> 00:33:25,367
And to do that, you have to relax.

348
00:33:26,869 --> 00:33:30,336
So your posture should be held up to the spine and everything else will happen.

349
00:33:32,932 --> 00:33:34,954
So relax on it.

350
00:33:34,974 --> 00:33:36,436
You relax on the object.

351
00:33:37,198 --> 00:33:40,803
And to keep the attention there, don't worry about concentration.

352
00:33:41,183 --> 00:33:41,403
See?

353
00:33:41,743 --> 00:33:42,506
Raise the interest.

354
00:33:43,145 --> 00:33:49,194
Just ask yourself, when did you ever lose concentration if you were interested in something?

355
00:33:49,214 --> 00:33:49,955
It comes naturally.

356
00:33:50,396 --> 00:33:54,082
If the interest isn't there, if there's boredom, then you have to save yourself.

357
00:33:54,102 --> 00:33:54,923
Well, now that's interesting.

358
00:33:56,961 --> 00:34:01,569
Any object which comes, you have to raise that sort of question mark.

359
00:34:01,971 --> 00:34:04,694
And it's a sort of childlike curiosity.

360
00:34:05,857 --> 00:34:07,661
And it's questioning, do I really know?

361
00:34:07,681 --> 00:34:09,103
Do I really know?

362
00:34:09,123 --> 00:34:12,789
So I sit there and I think, well, as we were discussing, fear.

363
00:34:13,130 --> 00:34:16,556
Do I really, really know what fear is before I name it?

364
00:34:18,519 --> 00:34:22,766
Do I really, really know what an emotion is before I conceptualize it?

365
00:34:25,295 --> 00:34:26,978
Because that's the process in the mind.

366
00:34:27,137 --> 00:34:37,134
First there's a sensation or a feeling, then there's some sort of labeling or perceptual process, and then the history comes in, and that's it.

367
00:34:38,516 --> 00:34:42,342
Even in very simple things like, you might see one of these flowers.

368
00:34:42,983 --> 00:34:45,527
So you might name it, you know, a rose or something.

369
00:34:45,568 --> 00:34:47,190
But do you know it?

370
00:34:47,431 --> 00:34:49,293
Do you know that particular rose?

371
00:34:51,721 --> 00:34:56,590
Or have you just looked at it and it's just fitted into a pattern of a rose so then you've seen it.

372
00:34:56,831 --> 00:35:04,547
But have you gone up and really looked at the colour, looked at the veins in the petals, seen the shape of the petals, have you actually smelt it?

373
00:35:07,452 --> 00:35:10,219
But we're happy just to say that's a rose and then we think we know it.

374
00:35:12,291 --> 00:35:22,882
So it's raising that sort of curiosity as to what is actually happening now and recognizing that that is the achievement.

375
00:35:23,402 --> 00:35:23,963
That's it.

376
00:35:24,884 --> 00:35:26,125
That's all the Buddha's teaching.

377
00:35:28,226 --> 00:35:31,289
Satipaṁya, awareness and intuitive intelligence.

378
00:35:32,371 --> 00:35:34,012
It's just the establishment of that.

379
00:35:34,914 --> 00:35:36,996
And it comes when you have right attitude.

380
00:35:37,255 --> 00:35:40,458
You just want to know what's happening now.

381
00:35:42,143 --> 00:35:45,527
So you just rest your eye on it.

382
00:35:46,307 --> 00:35:49,672
So you can practice this, practice that on ordinary things.

383
00:35:49,891 --> 00:35:54,197
So the next time you're just out in the garden there and a flower, just rest your eye on it.

384
00:35:56,099 --> 00:36:01,306
So you don't look for anything, just rest your eye on it and see what the perceptual faculty is doing.

385
00:36:02,226 --> 00:36:05,289
Observe how the mind observes the flower.

386
00:36:11,597 --> 00:36:11,677
Hmm?

387
00:36:12,467 --> 00:36:14,710
Just be aware of where the eyes are going.

388
00:36:19,916 --> 00:36:20,376
And that's it.

389
00:36:26,202 --> 00:36:34,150
And when you catch yourself with wrong effort and you know that because you get tight I mean the other side of course is that you lose energy and you fall asleep.

390
00:36:35,251 --> 00:36:37,414
That's not so painful.

391
00:36:37,974 --> 00:36:42,018
But the other side when you get tight and you start sort of

392
00:36:43,719 --> 00:36:53,963
feeling nasty about yourself and all that, then just go into the feelings of it, the sensations of it.

393
00:36:53,983 --> 00:36:57,291
There's something crept in there about achieving it, that's all.

394
00:37:01,539 --> 00:37:08,246
So, as you know, the mind's very subtle, it's very, you know, like, you think you're doing it right, and then you find out afterwards you weren't doing it right.

395
00:37:08,266 --> 00:37:10,527
But that's alright.

396
00:37:10,547 --> 00:37:13,210
Just to find out that you weren't doing it right is a step forward.

397
00:37:14,751 --> 00:37:21,018
And sometimes you find out you didn't do it right, and now you think, well, from now on I will do it right.

398
00:37:21,398 --> 00:37:23,920
And a little bit later you realise you've done it wrong again.

399
00:37:23,940 --> 00:37:27,384
So, that's alright.

400
00:37:27,905 --> 00:37:31,327
That's how slippery the mind is.

401
00:37:45,382 --> 00:37:55,592
Does that help?

402
00:37:55,612 --> 00:37:59,815
Any other questions?

403
00:37:59,876 --> 00:38:00,697
Anything else?

404
00:38:10,746 --> 00:38:11,726
Is it time for tea then?

